[{"id":"FT540513","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p>Respond to all parts of the question:</p>\n\n<p>(a) Define party polarization.</p>\n\n<p>(b) Identify a trend shown in the graph above.</p>\n\n<p>(c) Describe two causes of party polarization in Congress.</p>\n\n<p>(d) Describe one effect of party polarization on congressional policy making.</p>\n","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<img alt=\"The figure shows a graph titled PARTY POLARIZATION, 1879 TO 2007. Along the horizontal axis are equally spaced tickmarks showing, from left to right, every 8 years from 1879 to 2007. The vertical axis is labeled Ideological Distance Between the Parties, and there are equally spaced tickmarks , from bottom to top, ranging from zero to 1 There are two data curves on the graph, one for the House  and one for the Senate. The House curve begins at approximately zero point seven five on the vertical axis in 1879, has an overall increase until it reaches approximately zero point nine aroundlgoa, decreases to about zero point four five from around 1935 to 1950, and then increases to one point zero by 2007. The Senate curve begins above the House curve, at approximately zero point eight on the vertical axis in 1879. The Senate curve has an overall decrease until it reaches approximately zero point three around 1937, and then has an overall increase until it ends, at approximately zero point eight in 2007. \" height=\"424\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/f30a55ce52509d1a7f59ea119d8598a4/original.png\" width=\"718\">"}]}]